# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: snubber-circuits
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] A **flyback diode** (also called **freewheeling diode**) is any diode connected across an inductor used to eliminate flyback, which is the sudden voltage spike seen across an inductive load when its supply current is suddenly reduced or interrupted.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] It is used in circuits in which inductive loads are controlled by switches, and in switching power supplies and inverters.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Flyback circuits have been used since 1930 and were refined starting in 1950 for use in television receivers.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The word *flyback* comes from the horizontal movement of the electron beam in a cathode ray tube, because the beam flew back to begin the next horizontal line.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This diode is known by many other names, such as snubber diode, commutating diode, freewheeling diode, suppressor diode, clamp diode, or catch diode.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] 1 shows an inductor connected to a battery - a constant voltage source.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The resistor represents the small static resistance of the inductor's wire windings.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] When the switch is closed, the voltage from the battery is applied to the inductor, causing current from the battery's positive terminal to flow down through the inductor and resistor.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The increase in current causes a back EMF (voltage) across the inductor due to Faraday's law of induction which opposes the change in current.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] As the current rises, more voltage is dropped across the resistor and less across the inductor, until the current reaches a steady value of $I=V_{B}/R$ with all the battery voltage across the resistance and none across the inductance.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] However, the current drops rapidly when the switch is opened in Fig.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The inductor resists the drop in current by developing a very large induced voltage of polarity in the opposite direction of the battery, positive at the lower end of the inductor and negative at the upper end.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This voltage pulse, sometimes called the inductive "kick", which can be much larger than the battery voltage, appears across the switch contacts.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] It causes electrons to jump the air gap between the contacts, causing a momentary electric arc to develop across the contacts as the switch is opened.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The arc continues until the energy stored in the inductor's magnetic field is dissipated as heat in the arc.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The arc can damage the switch contacts, causing pitting and burning, eventually destroying them.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] If a transistor is used to switch the current, such as switching power supplies, the high reverse voltage can destroy the transistor.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] To prevent the inductive voltage pulse on turnoff, a diode is connected across the inductor, as shown in Fig.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The diode doesn't conduct current while the switch is closed because it is reverse-biased by the battery voltage, so it doesn't interfere with the normal operation of the circuit.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] However, when the switch is opened, the induced voltage across the inductor of opposite polarity forward biases the diode, and it conducts current, limiting the voltage across the inductor and thus preventing the arc from forming at the switch.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The inductor and diode momentarily form a loop or circuit powered by the stored energy in the inductor.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This circuit supplies a current path to the inductor to replace the current from the battery, so the inductor current does not drop abruptly and does not develop a high voltage.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The voltage across the inductor is limited to the forward voltage of the diode, around 0.7 - 1.5V.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This "freewheeling" or "flyback" current through the diode and inductor decreases slowly to zero as the magnetic energy in the inductor is dissipated as heat in the series resistance of the windings.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This may take a few milliseconds in a small inductor.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Oscilloscope trace showing inductive voltage spike in solenoid connected to a 24 VDC power supply.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] (50 V / division on the left, 1 V / division on the right).
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] These images show the voltage spike and its elimination through the use of a flyback diode (1N4007).
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] In this case, the inductor is a solenoid connected to a 24V DC power supply.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Each waveform was taken using a digital oscilloscope set to trigger when the voltage across the inductor dipped below zero.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] **Note the different scaling:** left image 50V/division, right image 1V/division.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] In Figure 1, the voltage as measured across the switch, bounces/spikes to around -300 V.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] In Figure 2, a flyback diode was added in antiparallel with the solenoid.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Instead of spiking to -300 V, the flyback diode only allows approximately -1.4 V of potential to be built up (-1.4 V is a combination of the forward bias of the 1N4007 diode (1.1 V) and the foot of wiring separating the diode and the solenoid).
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] The waveform in Figure 2 is also smoother than the waveform in Figure 1, perhaps due to arcing at the switch for Figure 1.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] In both cases, the total time for the solenoid to discharge is a few milliseconds, though the lower voltage drop across the diode will slow relay dropout.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] When used with a DC coil relay, a flyback diode can cause delayed drop-out of the contacts when power is removed, due to the continued circulation of current in the relay coil and diode.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] When rapid opening of the contacts is important, a resistor or reverse-biased Zener diode can be placed in series with the diode to help dissipate the coil energy faster, at the expense of higher voltage at the switch.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Schottky diodes are preferred in flyback diode applications for switching power converters because they have the lowest forward drop (~0.2 V rather than >0.7 V for low currents) and are able to quickly respond to reverse bias (when the inductor is being re-energized).
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] They, therefore, dissipate less energy while transferring energy from the inductor to a capacitor.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] According to Faraday's law of induction, if the current through an inductance changes, this inductance induces a voltage, so the current will flow as long as there is energy in the magnetic field.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] If the current can only flow through the air, the voltage is so high that the air conducts.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] That is why in mechanically switched circuits, the near-instantaneous dissipation which occurs without a flyback diode is often observed as an arc across the opening mechanical contacts.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Energy is dissipated in this arc primarily as intense heat, which causes undesirable premature erosion of the contacts.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Another way to dissipate energy is through electromagnetic radiation.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Similarly, for non-mechanical solid-state switching (i.e., a transistor), large voltage drops across an unactivated solid-state switch can destroy the component in question (either instantaneously or through accelerated wear and tear).
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Some energy is also lost from the system as a whole and from the arc as a broad spectrum of electromagnetic radiation, in the form of radio waves and light.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] These radio waves can cause undesirable clicks and pops on nearby radio receivers.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] To minimise the antenna-like radiation of this electromagnetic energy from wires connected to the inductor, the flyback diode should be connected as physically close to the inductor as practicable.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] This approach also minimises those parts of the circuit that are subject to an unwanted high-voltage — a good engineering practice.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] We observe that the current will decrease faster if the resistance is high, such as with air.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Now if we open the switch with the diode in place, we only need to consider *L*1, *R*1 and *D*1.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] We can calculate the time it needs to switch off by determining for which t it is *I*(*t*) = 0.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Flyback diodes are commonly used when semiconductor devices switch inductive loads off: in relay drivers, H-bridge motor drivers, and so on.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] A switched-mode power supply also exploits this effect, but the energy is not dissipated to heat and is instead used to pump a packet of additional charge into a capacitor, in order to supply power to a load.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] When the inductive load is a relay, the flyback diode can noticeably delay the release of the relay by keeping the coil current flowing longer.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] A resistor in series with the diode will make the circulating current decay faster at the drawback of an increased reverse voltage.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] A zener diode in series but with reverse polarity with regard to the flyback diode has the same properties, albeit with a fixed reverse voltage increase.
[src:snubber-circuits/flyback-diode] Both the transistor voltages and the resistor or zener diode power ratings should be checked in this case.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A **snubber** is a device used to suppress ("snub") a phenomenon such as voltage transients in electrical systems, pressure transients in fluid systems (caused by for example water hammer) or excess force or rapid movement in mechanical systems.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Snubbers are frequently used in electrical systems with an inductive load where the sudden interruption of current flow leads to a large counter-electromotive force: a rise in voltage across the current switching device that opposes the change in current, in accordance with Faraday's law.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] This transient can be a source of electromagnetic interference (EMI) in other circuits.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Additionally, if the voltage generated across the device is beyond what the device is intended to tolerate, it may damage or destroy it.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The snubber provides a short-term alternative current path around the current switching device so that the inductive element may be safely discharged.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Inductive elements are often unintentional, arising from the current loops implied by physical circuitry like long and/or tortuous wires.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] While current switching is everywhere, snubbers will generally only be required where a major current path is switched, such as in power supplies.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Snubbers are also often used to prevent arcing across the contacts of relays and switches, or electrical interference, or the welding of the contacts that can occur (see also arc suppression).
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A simple RC snubber uses a small resistor (R) in series with a small capacitor (C).
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] This combination can be used to suppress the rapid rise in voltage across a thyristor, preventing the erroneous turn-on of the thyristor; it does this by limiting the rate of rise in voltage ( $dV/dt$ ) across the thyristor to a value which will not trigger it.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] An appropriately designed RC snubber can be used with either DC or AC loads.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] This sort of snubber is commonly used with inductive loads such as electric motors.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The voltage across a capacitor cannot change instantaneously, so a decreasing transient current will flow through it for a fraction of a second, allowing the voltage across the switch to increase more slowly when the switch is opened.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Determination of voltage rating can be difficult owing to the nature of transient waveforms, and may be defined simply by the power rating of the snubber components and the application.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] RC snubbers can be made discretely and are also built as a single component (see also Boucherot cell).
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] When the current flowing is DC, a simple rectifier diode is often employed as a snubber.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The snubber diode is wired in parallel with an inductive load (such as a relay coil or electric motor).
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The diode is installed so that it does not conduct under normal conditions.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] When the external driving current is interrupted, the inductor current flows instead through the diode.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The stored energy of the inductor is then gradually dissipated by the diode voltage drop and the resistance of the inductor itself.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] One disadvantage of using a simple rectifier diode as a snubber is that the diode allows current to continue flowing for some time, causing the inductor to remain active for slightly longer than desired.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] When such a snubber is utilized in a relay, this effect may cause a significant delay in the *drop out*, or disengagement, of the actuator.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The diode must immediately enter into forward conduction mode as the driving current is interrupted.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Most ordinary diodes, even "slow" power silicon diodes, are able to turn on very quickly, in contrast to their slow reverse recovery time.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] These are sufficient for snubbing electromechanical devices such as relays and motors.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] In high-speed cases, where the switching is faster than 10 nanoseconds, such as in certain switching power regulators, "fast", "ultrafast", or Schottky diodes may be required.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] More sophisticated designs use a diode with an RC network.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] In some DC circuits, a varistor made of inexpensive metal oxide, called a metal oxide varistor (MOV) is used.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] They may be unipolar or bipolar, like two inverse-series silicon Zener diodes, but are prone to wear out after about a dozen max-rated joules of energy absorption such as lightning protection, but are suitable for lower energy.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Now with lower series resistance (Rs) in semiconductors they are generally called transient voltage suppressors (TVS), or surge protection devices (SPD).
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Transient voltage suppressors (TVS) may be used instead of the simple diode.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The coil diode clamp makes the relay turn off slower ( $T=L/R$ ) and thus increases contact arc if with a motor load which also needs a snubber.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] The diode clamp works well for coasting a uni-directional motor to a stop, but for bi-directional motors, a bipolar TVS is used.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A higher voltage Zener-like TVS may make the relay open faster than it would with a simple rectifier diode clamp, as R is higher while the voltage rises to the clamp level.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A Zener diode connected to ground will protect against positive transients that go over the Zener's breakdown voltage, and will protect against negative transients greater than a normal forward diode drop.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Transient-voltage-suppression diodes are like silicon controlled rectifiers (SCRs) which trigger from overvoltage then clamp like Darlington transistors for lower voltage drop over a longer time period.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] In AC circuits a rectifier diode snubber cannot be used; if a simple RC snubber is not adequate a more complex bidirectional snubber design must be used.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Snubbers for pipes and equipment are used to control movement during abnormal conditions such as earthquakes, turbine trips, safety valve closure, relief valve closure, or hydraulic fuse closure.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] Snubbers allow for free thermal movement of a component during regular conditions, but restrain the component in irregular conditions.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A hydraulic snubber allows for pipe deflection under normal operating conditions.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] When subjected to an impulse load, the snubber becomes activated and acts as a restraint in order to restrict pipe movement.
[src:snubber-circuits/rc-snubber] A mechanical snubber uses mechanical means to provide the restraint force.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A **transient-voltage-suppression** (**TVS**) **diode**, also **transil**, **transorb** or **thyrector**, is an electronic component used to protect electronics from voltage spikes induced on connected wires.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The device operates by shunting excess current when the induced voltage exceeds the avalanche breakdown potential.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It is a clamping device, suppressing all overvoltages above its breakdown voltage.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] It automatically resets when the overvoltage goes away, but absorbs much more of the transient energy internally than a similarly rated crowbar device.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode may be either unidirectional or bidirectional.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A unidirectional device operates as a rectifier in the forward direction like any other avalanche diode, but is made and tested to handle very large peak currents.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A bidirectional transient-voltage-suppression diode can be represented by two mutually opposing avalanche diodes in series with one another and connected in parallel with the circuit to be protected.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] While this representation is schematically accurate, physically the devices are now manufactured as a single component.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] A transient-voltage-suppression diode can respond to over-voltages faster than other common over-voltage protection components such as varistors or gas discharge tubes.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] The actual clamping occurs in roughly one picosecond, but in a practical circuit the inductance of the wires leading to the device imposes a higher limit.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] This makes transient-voltage-suppression diodes useful for protection against very fast and often damaging voltage transients.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] These fast over-voltage transients are present on all distribution networks and can be caused by either internal or external events, such as lightning or motor arcing.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] Transient voltage suppressors will fail if they are subjected to voltages or conditions beyond those that the particular product was designed to accommodate.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] There are three key modes in which the TVS will fail: short, open, and degraded device.
[src:snubber-circuits/transient-voltage-suppression-diode] TVS diodes are sometimes referred to as transorbs, from the Vishay trademark *TransZorb*.
